Human attitudes are a crucial driver of climate change, but they are neither the sole nor the most relevant influence. Climate change is a multifaceted phenomena that is influenced by human activities, environmental processes, and economic and political systems, among others. Human beliefs influence our behaviors and choices, but they are not the fundamental driver of climate change. This argument assumes that climate change is an issue that can be remedied by only altering human thinking. This is not the situation. Climate change is caused by a complex web of elements, and resolving it will need a multidimensional strategy that takes into account both human activity and natural processes. This involves lowering our reliance on fossil fuels, investing in renewable energy, and implementing energy efficiency measures. This argument also indicates that climate change is an issue that can be resolved by people acting alone. Likewise, this is not the case. Climate change is a global issue requiring a global solution. Local, national, and international collaboration is required to address the root causes of climate change and reduce its impacts. Finally, it is essential to recognize that the political and economic institutions in which we live determine our ideas. If we fail to address the root causes of climate change, we run the danger of prolonging the status quo rather than resolving the issue. In conclusion, human beliefs are a significant driver of climate change, but they are not the primary reason. Climate change is a complicated phenomena that is influenced by a wide range of elements and necessitates a diversified strategy that tackles both human activity and natural processes. Local, national, and international collaboration is required to address the root causes of climate change and reduce its impacts. 